        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'In {{spacex_s1}}, find the specific accounting policy notes about the reorganization of entities under common control, the mergers with xAI and X Holdings, and any discussion of fair value, step-up in basis, or purchase price allocation. Also find any discussion about what would be different under purchase accounting (ASC 805) and what standalone historical information for SpaceX is no longer separately determinable or observable.'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Common-Control Reorganization Accounting for the xAI and X Mergers\n\nBelow is every relevant passage from the provided text, organized by the specific topics you asked about.\n\n---\n\n## 1. The Accounting Framework: Common-Control Reorganization\n\nThe foundational policy statement appears in the preamble and is repeated throughout:\n\n> **"The Mergers have been accounted for as reorganizations of entities under common control as Mr. Elon Musk had a controlling financial interest in the Company, xAI and X through his majority voting interest in each such entity during the years presented in these consolidated financial statements."**\n\nThis is the single most important sentence. Because Elon Musk held majority voting interest in **all three entities simultaneously**, the accounting treatment is not a purchase/business combination under ASC 805 — it is a reorganization under common control. The "acquiring" entity (SpaceX) merely absorbs entities that were already effectively under the same ultimate control.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Retrospective Combination at Historical Carrying Amounts (No Fair Value, No Step-Up, No Goodwill)\n\nThe text states explicitly and repeatedly:\n\n> **"The Company\'s consolidated financial statements have been prepared to reflect the retrospective combination of the net assets of the entities at their historical carrying amounts for all periods presented."**\n\nAnd:\n\n> **"No new goodwill or other intangible assets have been recorded."**\n\nThis is the critical distinction. Under a common-control reorganization:\n\n- **No purchase price allocation (PPA)** is performed.\n- **No step-up in basis** of acquired assets to fair value.\n- **No goodwill** is recognized.\n- **No new intangible assets** are recorded (e.g., no customer relationships, no technology intangibles, no brand value from the X/Twitter acquisition or the xAI acquisition).\n\nAll assets and liabilities of X Holdings (Twitter/X), X.AI Corp., and xAI are carried at their **pre-existing historical book values** as if they had always been part of SpaceX\'s consolidated group.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Elimination of Intercompany Transactions\n\nThe text states:\n\n> **"All historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation."**\n\nThis is reinforced in the accounting policies note (Note 2):\n\n> **"The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of the Company and its wholly owned subsidiaries. All intercompany balances and transactions have been eliminated in consolidation."**\n\nAny transactions that occurred between SpaceX, xAI, X Holdings, and X.AI Corp. during the historical periods — for example, SpaceX providing launch services to xAI, or xAI providing AI compute to X — are **removed** in the consolidated presentation. This prevents double-counting of revenue and expenses among entities that are now combined.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Capital Stock and Equity Adjustments\n\nThe text explains how equity is presented:\n\n> **"The capital stock and shareholders\' equity for all periods presented reflects a continuation of the historical SpaceX capital stock and shareholders\' equity, combined with the historical capital stock and shareholders\' equity of X and xAI merged under common control, as adjusted by the respective exchange ratios used to effect the Mergers."**\n\nThe exchange ratios were:\n\n- **X Merger (March 28, 2025):** Each class of X Holdings Corp. common stock converted into **2.776 shares** of xAI Common Stock of the same class. Each class of X.AI Corp. common stock converted into **1.000 share** of xAI Common Stock of the same class.\n- **xAI Merger (February 2, 2026):** Each share of xAI Common Stock converted into **0.1433 shares** of SpaceX Common Stock (on a pre-2026 Stock Split basis).\n\nThese ratios are applied **retroactively** to all historical share counts. The combined exchange ratio for X Holdings common stock into SpaceX common stock would therefore be 2.776 × 0.1433 = **0.3978 SpaceX shares per X Holdings share**.\n\nThe text also notes:\n\n> **"No fractional SpaceX shares were issued and all share amounts were rounded up to the nearest whole number."**\n\nAnd:\n\n> **"Any shares of xAI Common Stock previously held by the Company were canceled and retired and did not receive any consideration."** (Elimination of treasury-equivalent cross-holdings.)\n\n---\n\n## 5. Treatment of xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock — The Exception\n\nOne important nuance is how xAI\'s preferred stock was handled differently:\n\n> **"The capital stock and shareholders\' equity for all periods presented reflects a continuation of the historical SpaceX capital stock and shareholders\' equity, combined with the historical capital stock and shareholders\' equity of X and xAI merged under common control, as adjusted by the respective exchange ratios used to effect the Mergers, **except for xAI\'s historical redeemable convertible preferred stock.**"**\n\nAnd in more detail:\n\n> **"Although xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock converted into SpaceX Common Stock upon the xAI Merger closing, the xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock balances are presented as Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock in the consolidated financial statements for all periods presented."**\n\n> **"Because the xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock was legally outstanding during all historical periods prior to the xAI Merger and represented a separate equity class of a legally distinct predecessor entity, the conversion of xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock into SpaceX Common Stock is recognized only in the period in which the exchange actually occurs, and not retrospectively."**\n\n> **"Accordingly, the historical consolidated balance sheets and consolidated statements of redeemable convertible preferred stock and shareholders\' equity reflect the xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock as outstanding xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock consistent with its legal form and rights during those periods and are not recast on an as-converted basis."**\n\n> **"The impact of the conversion will be presented prospectively in the period of the merger (Q1 2026)."**\n\nSo while xAI **common stock** is retroactively shown as-if-converted into SpaceX common stock for all periods, xAI\'s **redeemable convertible preferred stock** remains on the balance sheet as its own class through the merger date, and only converts to SpaceX common stock in Q1 2026.\n\nThe preferred stock tables show this: as of December 31, 2025, xAI\'s Series A through Series E Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock are listed separately with their own dividend rates, initial prices, authorized shares, outstanding shares, liquidation preferences, and net carrying values (totaling ~$31.7 billion net carrying value across ~1.9 billion shares outstanding).\n\nThe conversion terms for the preferred stock upon the xAI Merger closing were:\n\n> **"each share of xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock (other than xAI Series A Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock) was converted into 75.46 shares of SpaceX Class B Common Stock per preferred share (on a pre-2026 Stock Split basis)."**\n\nFor Series A specifically, eligible service providers could elect cash of $75.46 per share instead.\n\n---\n\n## 6. The Warrant Treatment\n\n> **"xAI also issued warrants to customer that were outstanding as of the effective date of the xAI Merger, which had a ten-year term originally set to expire in 2035, with an exercise price equal to the par value of the stock, and vesting terms that resulted in the warrants vesting proportionally to the payments received under the related agreement. The closing of the xAI Merger triggered an acceleration clause in which all outstanding xAI warrants, both vested and unvested components, were automatically exercised on a cashless basis and converted into fully vested SpaceX Class A Common Stock at the exchange ratio of 0.1433 (on a pre-2026 Stock Split basis)."**\n\n---\n\n## 7. Change in Reporting Entity\n\nThe text explicitly identifies this as a change in reporting entity (rather than a business combination):\n\n> **"This presentation constitutes a change in reporting entity."**\n\nUnder ASC 805 (Business Combinations), an acquisition of a business from an unrelated party requires purchase accounting — recognizing assets at fair value, recording goodwill, etc. Under common-control transactions, the guidance is different (primarily in ASC 805-50 and related guidance): the receiving entity combines the net assets at historical cost and recasts prior periods as if the entities had always been combined.\n\n---\n\n## 8. What Would Be Different Under Purchase Accounting (ASC 805)\n\nThe text **does not explicitly discuss** ASC 805 or what would differ under purchase accounting. However, the following statements are the **inverse** of what purchase accounting would require — each negation implicitly tells you what purchase accounting would do:\n\n| What the text says (common control) | What purchase accounting (ASC 805) would require |\n|---|---|\n| "No new goodwill or other intangible assets have been recorded" | Goodwill and identifiable intangible assets (customer relationships, technology, brand/trademarks) would be recognized at fair value |\n| "Retrospective combination of the net assets of the entities at their historical carrying amounts" | Assets and liabilities would be measured at acquisition-date fair value (step-up in basis) |\n| "All historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation" | This would also occur under purchase accounting, but the period in which the elimination begins would be the acquisition date, not retrospectively |\n| "Separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided" | The pre-acquisition historical financials of the acquiree would typically be disclosed separately in business combination disclosures |\n| The transaction is characterized as a "change in reporting entity" | It would be characterized as a business combination with required disclosures of purchase price allocation, contingent consideration, acquisition-related costs, etc. |\n\nThe practical significance is enormous. Given that:\n- X Holdings (Twitter) was acquired by Musk in October 2022 (likely at a significant premium to any prior book value, after which Musk made substantial investments)\n- xAI was founded in 2023 and raised billions in capital (Series A through E preferred stock with net carrying values totaling ~$31.7 billion)\n- The combined liquidation preference of all xAI preferred stock alone is ~$31.7 billion\n\nUnder purchase accounting, SpaceX would need to:\n1. Determine the fair value of consideration transferred\n2. Fair-value all assets and liabilities of xAI and X Holdings (including the X/Twitter platform, user base, Grok AI models, infrastructure, etc.)\n3. Record any difference as goodwill\n4. Amortize finite-lived intangible assets prospectively\n\nNone of this occurs under common-control accounting. The historical book values carry through unchanged.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Standalone Historical Information That Is No Longer Separately Determinable\n\nThe text states:\n\n> **"As the consolidated financial statements already reflect the reorganization of entities under common control for all periods presented, separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided."**\n\nThis is the key statement. Because all periods have been **retrospectively recast** to present SpaceX, xAI, X Holdings, and X.AI Corp. as a single combined entity:\n\n- **SpaceX\'s standalone historical financial statements** (prior to absorbing xAI and X) are **no longer separately presented** or determinable from the consolidated statements\n- **xAI\'s standalone historical financial statements** are not separately provided\n- **X Holdings\' (Twitter/X) standalone historical financial statements** are not separately provided\n- **X.AI Corp.\'s standalone historical financial statements** are not separately provided\n\nThe financial statements show **only the combined, consolidated view** for all periods. A reader cannot extract, for example, what SpaceX\'s revenue or net income was in 2024 **without** X/Twitter and xAI included, because those figures have been combined retroactively.\n\nAdditionally, the elimination of intercompany transactions means that the standalone economics of inter-entity relationships (e.g., SpaceX launching Starlink satellites that serve X\'s infrastructure, or xAI providing Grok capabilities to the X platform) are invisible in the consolidated presentation.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe accounting treatment is a **common-control reorganization** — not a purchase/business combination — because Elon Musk controlled all entities throughout. The key consequences are:\n\n1. **No fair value step-up** of any assets or liabilities\n2. **No goodwill or new intangible assets** recognized\n3. **Historical carrying amounts** are preserved\n4. **Retrospective recasting** of all periods (as if the entities had always been combined)\n5. **Intercompany transactions eliminated** for all periods\n6. **Exchange ratios** (2.776x for X → xAI; 0.1433x for xAI → SpaceX) applied retroactively to share counts, with a 5-for-1 stock split also retroactively applied\n7. **xAI preferred stock** treated as its own class until conversion at merger close (not retrospectively recast)\n8. **No standalone historical statements** are provided for any of the individual predecessor entities\n9. The entire presentation is classified as a **change in reporting entity**, not a business combination',
