        output='## Historical Information No Longer Observable Under Common-Control Accounting Relative to Purchase Accounting\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 filed May 20, 2026 explicitly states that the mergers with xAI (completed February 2, 2026) and X Holdings (completed via xAI on March 28, 2025) "have been accounted for as reorganizations of entities under common control as Mr. Elon Musk had a controlling financial interest in the Company, xAI and X through his majority voting interest in each such entity during the years presented." This treatment — a "change in reporting entity" rather than a business combination under ASC 805 — renders several categories of historical information **no longer observable**:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Standalone Historical Financial Performance of Each Predecessor Entity\n\nThe filing states: *"As the consolidated financial statements already reflect the reorganization of entities under common control for all periods presented, separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided."*\n\nUnder **common-control accounting**, all historical periods are **retrospectively recast** to present SpaceX, xAI, X Holdings, and X.AI Corp. as a single combined entity from inception. This means:\n\n- **SpaceX\'s standalone revenue, margins, net income, and balance sheet** for any period prior to the mergers are **no longer separately determinable** from the consolidated statements.\n- **xAI\'s standalone financial statements** are not separately provided.\n- **X Holdings\' (Twitter/X) standalone financial statements** are not separately provided.\n\nUnder **purchase accounting**, the acquirer\'s pre-acquisition financials would remain intact, and the acquiree\'s pre-acquisition financials would typically be disclosed separately in business combination disclosures. An investor could compare the standalone acquirer\'s historical performance to the post-combination performance.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Fair Value of Acquired Assets and Liabilities (No Step-Up in Basis)\n\nThe filing states: *"The Company\'s consolidated financial statements have been prepared to reflect the retrospective combination of the net assets of the entities at their historical carrying amounts for all periods presented."*\n\nUnder common-control accounting, all assets and liabilities of xAI and X Holdings are carried at their **pre-existing historical book values** — the same values recorded on the predecessor entities\' books prior to the mergers.\n\nUnder **purchase accounting (ASC 805)**, all acquired assets and assumed liabilities would be measured at **acquisition-date fair value** (a "step-up" in basis). This would reveal:\n- The fair value of X/Twitter\'s platform, user base, content, data center infrastructure, and other tangible assets\n- The fair value of xAI\'s technology, Grok AI models, compute infrastructure, and intellectual property\n- Fair value adjustments to debt, lease obligations, and other liabilities\n\n**None of these fair values are observable** in the filing because no purchase price allocation was performed.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Goodwill and Identifiable Intangible Assets\n\nThe filing states explicitly: *"No new goodwill or other intangible assets have been recorded."*\n\nUnder purchase accounting, the difference between the consideration transferred and the net fair value of acquired assets and liabilities would be recorded as **goodwill**, and separately identifiable intangible assets (customer relationships, technology, brand/trademarks, in-process R&D) would be recognized and amortized over their useful lives.\n\nUnder common-control accounting:\n- **No goodwill is recognized** from the mergers\n- **No new intangible assets** are recorded (e.g., no customer relationship assets from X/Twitter\'s ~600M+ user base, no technology intangibles from Grok AI)\n- There is **no observable indication of the implied premium** Musk paid (or the implied enterprise value) for these combined entities\n\nThis is particularly significant given that X Holdings was acquired by Musk in October 2022 (reportedly at ~$44 billion), and xAI raised over $31.7 billion in preferred capital across Series A through E rounds. Under purchase accounting, the fair value of consideration transferred and resulting goodwill would have been disclosed.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Purchase Price Allocation and Acquisition-Related Disclosures\n\nUnder purchase accounting, ASC 805 requires detailed disclosures including:\n- The fair value of consideration transferred\n- Contingent consideration arrangements\n- Acquisition-related costs\n- Revenue and earnings of the acquiree since the acquisition date\n- Pro forma combined results as if the acquisition had occurred at the beginning of the period\n\n**None of these disclosures are provided** in the filing. The common-control approach requires none of them, rendering this information unobservable.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Intercompany Transaction Economics\n\nThe filing states: *"All historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation."*\n\nUnder common-control accounting, intercompany transactions are eliminated **for all historical periods** (retroactively). This means the standalone economics of relationships such as SpaceX providing launch services to xAI, or xAI providing AI capabilities to the X platform, are **invisible** in all periods presented.\n\nUnder purchase accounting, intercompany elimination would begin only from the **acquisition date forward**, and pre-acquisition related-party transactions would still be visible in the acquirer\'s historical standalone statements.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Individual Entity Capital Structures and Equity History\n\nThe filing explains that capital stock and shareholders\' equity is presented as *"a continuation of the historical SpaceX capital stock and shareholders\' equity, combined with the historical capital stock and shareholders\' equity of X and xAI merged under common control, as adjusted by the respective exchange ratios."*\n\nThe exchange ratios (2.776× for X → xAI; 0.1433× for xAI → SpaceX, pre-stock-split) are applied retroactively. This means:\n- **Individual entity equity structures** (authorized shares, classes, preferences) are blended\n- **Historical share counts** reflect the combined, as-converted view rather than the actual shares outstanding of each standalone entity\n- The only exception is **xAI\'s redeemable convertible preferred stock**, which is presented as its own class until the merger date (not retrospectively recast)\n\nUnder purchase accounting, the acquirer\'s historical equity structure would remain intact, and only the post-acquisition equity structure would reflect the combination.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Information Category | Observable Under Purchase Accounting | Observable Under Common-Control (as filed) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Standalone financials of SpaceX | ✅ Pre-acquisition periods preserved | ❌ Blended with xAI and X for all periods |\n| Standalone financials of acquirees (xAI, X) | ✅ Typically disclosed separately | ❌ Not provided |\n| Fair value of acquired assets/liabilities | ✅ Measured at acquisition-date fair value | ❌ Carried at historical book value |\n| Goodwill from mergers | ✅ Recognized as residual | ❌ Not recorded |\n| Identifiable intangible assets | ✅ Separately recognized and amortized | ❌ Not recorded |\n| Purchase price allocation details | ✅ Required under ASC 805 | ❌ Not applicable |\n| Pre-acquisition intercompany transactions | ✅ Visible in standalone acquirer statements | ❌ Eliminated retroactively for all periods |\n| Individual entity capital structures | ✅ Acquirer\'s historical equity preserved | ❌ Blended retroactively |\n\n**Bottom line:** The common-control accounting treatment means that investors cannot observe the **standalone financial profile of SpaceX prior to absorbing xAI and X**, the **fair value of the combined enterprise\'s assets** (particularly the X/Twitter platform and xAI\'s AI technology), the **implied goodwill or premium** inherent in the transactions, or the **individual operating economics** of each predecessor entity. All historical data is a blended, retrospective consolidation at historical book values — a fundamentally different informational lens than purchase accounting would provide.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=True,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=0.0,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
